Title: Corporate Ownership Around the World 
Abstract:
 We use data on ownership structures of large corporations in 27 wealthy
 economies to identify the ultimate controlling shareholders of these
 firms. We find that, except in economies with very good shareholder
 protection, relatively few of these firms are widely held, in contrast to
 Berle and Means's image of ownership of the modern corporation. Rather,
 these firms are typically controlled by families or the State. Equity
 control by financial institutions is far less common. The controlling
 shareholders typically have power over firms significantly in excess of
 their cash flow rights, primarily through the use of pyramids and
 participation in management. Copyright The American Finance Association 1999. 
