Title: Can Costs of Consumption Adjustment Explain Asset Pricing Puzzles? 
Abstract:
 We investigate Grossman and Laroque's (1990) conjecture that costs of
 adjusting consumption can account, in part, for the empirical failure of
 the consumption-based capital asset pricing model (CCAPM). We incorporate
 small fixed costs of consumption adjustment into a CCAPM with
 heterogeneous agents. We find that undetectably small consumption
 adjustment costs can account for much of the discrepancy between the
 observed variance of nondurable aggregate consumption growth and the
 predictions of the CCAPM, and can partially reconcile nondurable
 consumption data with the observed equity premium. We conclude that the
 CCAPM's implications are nonrobust to extremely small adjustment costs. Copyright The American Finance Association 1999. 
