Title: The Relationship between Firm Investment and Financial Status 
Abstract:
 Firm investment decisions are shown to be directly related to financial
 factors. Investment decisions of firms with high creditworthiness
 (according to traditional financial ratios) are extremely sensitive to the
 availability of internal funds; less creditworthy firms are much less
 sensitive to internal fund availability. This large sample evidence is
 based on an objective sorting mechanism and supports the results of Kaplan
 and Zingales (1997), who also find that investment outlays of the least
 constrained firms are the most sensitive to internal cash flow. Copyright The American Finance Association 1999. 
