Author-Workplace-Name: University of Georgia, Athens 
Title: Differences in Trading Behavior across NYSE Specialist Firms 
Abstract:
 Using a sample of NYSE-listed equities from 1992, this study examines
 whether market maker performance differs across specialist firms. We find
 that spreads and depth differ across specialist firms, but the
 competitiveness of NYSE quotes relative to other exchanges does not appear
 to be affected by these differences. Differences are also evident in
 measures of transitory volatility and in the frequency and duration of
 order-imbalance trading halts. The results suggest that specialists have a
 significant effect on execution costs, liquidity, and noise in security
 prices and that these effects are not completely eliminated by competition
 or the NYSE's monitoring mechanisms. Copyright The American Finance Association 1999. 
